arch:property.oc:show_val: This locus is fill located in the northwest corner of the trench. It touches the walls of L157 and is outside the Ubaid house. We believe that at least half of this locus is a part of L156 becasue the soil is the same. It has traces of the same surface present in L164 and the color and texture of the soil is the same as L156. It is its own locus because it did not present the same traces of surface that were present in L156, L164, L166, or L168. Either it is different, or its preservation of the relevant material is bad. As stated above it has similar soil and context to these loci, and thus is thought to be at least contemporary. To dig it we have gone down to the same level as the abutting surfaces, keeping them roughly together in depth so as to notice any relevant differences between the two. About 35cm down we discovered that there were multiple mudbricks on the ground. Looking at the baulk, these mudbricks continue up into the baulk for about 30cm with 4 courses that we can see. Obviously we cut through them and didn"t see them until now. Additionally about 20cm north of these bricks is an incomplete line of stones.

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
